Integrating Grafana alerts with Slack using webhooks involves two main steps: 
setting up an Incoming Webhook in Slack and configuring a Webhook contact point in Grafana.

1. Set up Incoming Webhook in Slack:
Create a Slack App: Navigate to the Slack API website  https://api.slack.com/apps?new_app=1

 and create a new Slack app for your workspace.


Enable Incoming Webhooks: Within your app's settings, go to "Features" > "Incoming Webhooks" and activate this feature.
Add a New Webhook to Workspace: Click "Add New Webhook to Workspace," choose the desired Slack channel for notifications, and authorize the app.
Copy Webhook URL: Slack will provide a unique Webhook URL. Copy this URL, as it will be used in Grafana.
2. Configure Webhook Contact Point in Grafana:
Navigate to Contact Points: In Grafana, hover over the Alerting (bell) icon in the sidebar and click "Contact points."
Add New Contact Point: Click "+ Add contact point."
Configure Webhook Integration:
Provide a descriptive "Name" for the contact point (e.g., "Slack Webhook").
From the "Integration" list, select "Webhook."
Paste the copied Slack Webhook URL into the "URL" field.
(Optional) Customize settings such as HTTP method, authentication, and message content if needed.
Save and Test: Click "Save contact point." You can then click "Test" and "Send test notification" to verify the integration and ensure alerts are successfully sent to your Slack channel. 
3. Create or Update Alert Rules:
When creating or editing an alert rule in Grafana, ensure that the newly created Slack Webhook contact point is selected as a notification destination for that rule.



Create a Kubernetes Dashboard in Grafana with Variables
Step 1: Create a New Dashboard
Open Grafana → left menu → Dashboards → + New Dashboard.
Click Add a new panel (this will be our first chart).
Keep it empty for now.

Step 2: Add Variables
Variables make dashboards interactive.
🔹 Add Namespace Variable
Go to Dashboard settings (⚙️) → Variables → Add variable.
Name: namespace
Type: Query
Data source: Prometheus
Query:
label_values(kube_pod_info, namespace)
 This lists all namespaces from Kubernetes.
Click Update.

🔹 Add Pod Variable
Again, Add variable.
Name: pod
Type: Query
Data source: Prometheus
Query:
label_values(kube_pod_info{namespace="$namespace"}, pod)
This filters pods based on the selected namespace.
Enable Multi-value (so you can select multiple pods).
Click Update.

Step 3: Create Panels
🔹 Panel 1: CPU Usage per Pod
Add a new panel.
Query (Prometheus):
sum(rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total{namespace="$namespace", pod=~"$pod"}[5m])) by (pod)
 This shows CPU usage of selected pods.
Visualization: Time series.
Title: CPU Usage (per Pod).

🔹 Panel 2: Memory Usage per Pod
Add a new panel.
Query:
sum(container_memory_usage_bytes{namespace="$namespace", pod=~"$pod"}) by (pod)
 Shows memory consumption per pod.
Visualization: Time series.
Title: Memory Usage (per Pod).

🔹 Panel 3: Pod Restarts
Add a new panel.
Query:
increase(kube_pod_container_status_restarts_total{namespace="$namespace", pod=~"$pod"}[30m])
 Shows container restarts in the last 30 minutes.
Visualization: Bar chart or Time series.
Title: Pod Restarts.

🔹 Panel 4: Node CPU Utilization
Add a new panel.
Query:
100 - (avg by(node) (rate(node_cpu_seconds_total{mode="idle"}[5m])) * 100)
 Shows percentage CPU usage per node.
Title: Node CPU Utilization.

Step 4: Save Dashboard
Click Save → give it a name like “Kubernetes Overview”.
At the top, you should now see dropdowns: namespace and pod.
 
Step 5: Test
Select a namespace (e.g., default).
Select a pod (e.g., nginx-123).
Watch panels update dynamically
 
 































